        <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:0.9rem; line-height:1.75; color:#4a4540; margin-top:0.75rem; padding-right:2rem;">Carina Heights has a mix of post-war homes, brick houses from the 1970s and 1980s, and a growing number of renovated properties that have taken advantage of the suburb's elevated topography and city views. The block sizes tend to be generous by inner-east standards.</p>
      </details>

      <details style="padding:1.25rem 0;">
        <summary style="font-family:var(--font-serif); font-size:1.05rem; cursor:pointer; color:#1c1917; list-style:none; display:flex; justify-content:space-between; align-items:center; gap:1rem;">
          Is Carina Heights a good suburb to invest in?
          <span style="color:#c4912a; font-size:1.4rem; flex-shrink:0;">+</span>
        </summary>
        <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:0.9rem; line-height:1.75; color:#4a4540; margin-top:0.75rem; padding-right:2rem;">Carina Heights offers solid value for investors seeking established housing close to Carindale Westfield and with good access to the inner east. Rental demand is steady from families who prioritise school catchments and space, and price growth has been consistent in recent years.</p>
      </details>

